<m0>PUERTO RICO <m1> <ql>
<ue5><m0>Senate expels member <ql>
over tax allegations <ql>
<m1><ue5><ep>
<m0>   <m0>SAN JUAN <m0>(--) The island Senate voted 23-6 Thursday to expel Sen. Nicolas Nogueras from the legislature because of allegations of local tax evasion.<ep>
   It was the first expulsion in the history of the 44-year-old Senate.<ep>
   On Wednesday, Nogueras became the first Puerto Rican senator to be indicted by a federal grand jury, on separate U.S. tax evasion charges. Also indicted were Nogueras' wife, Abigail Mojica, and the former federal tax collector for Puerto Rico, Jose M. Torres Duen~o.<ql>
<m1><styl>rdup,1<ql>
<ue5><m0>Companies, executive <ql>
convicted for oil spill <ql>
<m1><ue5><ep>
<m0>   <m0>SAN JUAN <m0>(--) Three corporations and an executive were convicted Thursday of federal charges in connection with a 1994 oil spill that damaged more than six miles of Puerto Rican beaches.<ep>
   The barge Morris J. Bergman ran aground in the early morning hours of Jan. 7, 1994, off northern Escambron Beach, spilling 750,000 gallons of heavy oil. <ep>
  Bunker Group Puerto Rico, Bunker Group Inc. and New England Marine Services were found guilty Thursday by a U.S. District Court jury of violating the 1972 Ports and Waterways Safety Act, the Oil Pollution Act of 1990 and charges of sending an unseaworthy vessel to sea. The jury also convicted Pedro Rivera, general manager of Bunker Group.<ql>
